randoop.types

Class ReferenceType

  • java.lang.Object
    • randoop.types.GeneralType
      • randoop.types.ReferenceType
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    AbstractTypeVariable, ArrayType, ClassOrInterfaceType, NullReferenceType

    public abstract class ReferenceType
extends GeneralType
    A reference type in JLS (Section 4.3) is defined as one of Class/Interface type, Array type, or a type variable.

      • isAssignableFrom

        public boolean isAssignableFrom(GeneralType sourceType)
        Indicates whether a value of a GeneralType can be assigned to a variable of this type: Variablethis = Expressionsourcetype. In other words, this is a legal assignment. Based on the definition of assignment context in section 5.2 of the JDK 8 Java Language Specification a value of one type is assignable to a variable of another type if the first type can be converted to the second by
        • an identity conversion (section 5.1.1),
        • a widening primitive conversion (section 5.1.2),
        • a widening reference conversion (section 5.1.5),
        • a boxing conversion (5.1.7), and
        • an unboxing conversion (section 5.1.8) possibly followed by a widening conversion.
        And, if after all those conversions, the type is a raw type, an unchecked conversion may occur.

        When implementing this method, be aware that the method Class.isAssignableFrom(Class) checks identity and reference conversions, and does a comparison of raw types for parameterized types. The method PrimitiveTypes.isAssignable(Class, Class) checks identity and primitive widening for primitive types.

        For ReferenceType, checks for widening reference conversion. See section 5.1.5 of JLS of JavaSE 8 for details.

        Overrides:
        isAssignableFrom in class GeneralType
        Parameters:
        sourceType - the type to test for assignability
        Returns:
        true if this type can be assigned from the source type, and false otherwise

      • isCaptureVariable

        boolean isCaptureVariable()
        Indicates whether this type is a capture type variable as constructed by InstantiatedType.applyCaptureConversion(). A capture type variable can only occur as a type argument in an InstantiatedType constructed this way.
        Returns:
        true if this type is a capture type variable, false otherwise

      • getSuperclass

        public ReferenceType getSuperclass()
        Return the type for the superclass for this type. Returns null for types that do not have a superclass. Provides the default for reference type objects, which is the Object type. (Note that this is different behavior than in reflection classes, where null is returned because Object has no superclass.)
        Overrides:
        getSuperclass in class GeneralType
        Returns:
        the Object class type

      • forClass

        public static ReferenceType forClass(java.lang.Class<?> classType)
        Returns a ReferenceType object for the given Class object. Only checks for arrays, classes, and interfaces; since type variables are only represented by Type references. For arrays, calls ArrayType.forClass(Class). For other (class/interface) types, calls ClassOrInterfaceType.forClass(Class).
        Parameters:
        classType - the Class object representing the type
        Returns:
        the ReferenceType object for the given type

      • forType

        public static ReferenceType forType(java.lang.reflect.Type type)
        Creates a ReferenceType for the given java.lang.reflect.Type. First, checks that the reference is not one of the direct subtypes of Type representing reference types (GenericArrayType or TypeVariable). Then checks that the reference is not a Class object representing an array. If the reference is none of those, returns the result of converting the type to a class or interface type.
        Parameters:
        type - the type reference
        Returns:
        the ReferenceType for the given Type
